<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLLEGE WORLD SERIES; 
</P>
<P>
CITADEL NEEDS 12 INNINGS, BUT SENDS FULLERTON HOME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
OMAHA, Neb. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tony Skole singled home Anthony Jenkins in the 12th inning Monday to lift The 
Citadel to an 8-7 victory over Cal State Fullerton in an elimination game of 
the College World Series. 
</P>
<P>
Jenkins singled to open the inning, moved up on a wild pitch by Chris Robinson 
(3-4) and came home on Skole's single to right. 
</P>
<P>
Skole's single in the 10th inning drove in Chris Coker for a 7-6 Citadel lead. 
But Fullerton tied it in the bottom of the inning when Kevin Farlow singled, 
took third on a sacrifice and an infield single, and scored on Phil Nevin's 
single to left. 
</P>
<P>
Hank Kraft (4-1), who pitched out of a bases-loaded, one-out jam in the 10th, 
ended the game by striking out Mate Borgogno with the tying run at third. 
</P>
<P>
The Citadel (46-13), at No. 7 the lowest remaining seed in the tournament, 
faces another elimination game Tuesday night against the loser of Monday 
night's Louisiana State-Oklahoma State game. 
</P>
<P>
Fullerton (36-23) led, 4-1, early but had to come back from a 6-4 deficit in 
the eighth to force extra innings. 
</P>
<P>
Paul Bunch walked to open the eighth, went to third on a single by Dave Ayala 
and scored when catcher Larry Hutto threw wildly to second on Ayala's steal 
attempt. Ayala went to third on the play and scored the tying run on Domingo 
Mota's single. 
</P>
<P>
Doubles by Jenkins and Coker gave The Citadel a 1-0 lead in the first. 
Fullerton tied it in the second when Frank Charles scored from second on 
Farlow's two-out single. 
</P>
<P>
The Titans scored twice in the third after Nevin reached base on a throwing 
error by shortstop Scott Elvington, one of seven Citadel miscues that led to 
three unearned runs. Nevin scored from second on a single by Borgogno, who came 
around on singles by Matt Hattabaugh and Charles. 
</P>
<P>
Fullerton made it 4-1 in the sixth, when Farlow singled and went to second when 
Elvington booted Ayala's potential double-play grounder. Mota grounded to 
second baseman Dan McDonnell, who stepped on second for the force. McDonnell's 
relay throw to first was in the dirt and Farlow scored. 
</P>
<P>
Billy Baker's home run leading off the seventh brought the Citadel to within 
4-2, and the Bulldogs made it 4-3 when Jason Rychlick reached base on Farlow's 
fielding error at shortstop and scored out later on McDonnell's double. 
</P>
<P>
Baker singled in a run and Rychlick had a two-run, two-out single to give the 
Citadel a 6-4 lead in the eighth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA060590-0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 229144 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 5, 1990, Tuesday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 6; Column 1; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
653 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PADRES DRAFT HARD-THROWING, TEXAS HIGH SCHOOL LEFT-HANDER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT MILLER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Padres went for youth and power Monday with their first-round choice in the 
major league draft. 
</P>
<P>
They used their pick -- 25th -- on left-handed pitcher Robbie Beckett, a 
hard-thrower from McCallum High School in Austin, Tex. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a great feeling to know the Padres wanted me," Beckett said. "I'm happy 
about it." 
</P>
<P>
Beckett, 6-feet-5 and 225 pounds, went 5-6 this season with a 3.05 earned-run 
average. 
</P>
<P>
But those aren't the numbers that tell Beckett's story. The important ones: 
First, he is 17. Next, take a look at this: in 70 innings this season, he 
allowed just 27 hits, struck out 128 -- and walked 127. But he throws in the 
90-mile-per-hour range, and the Padres figure he can work out the control 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
"You can correct a control problem," Padre Manager Jack McKeon said. "If a guy 
doesn't have a good arm, you can't correct that." 
</P>
<P>
Beckett said he was watching a movie when Padre scout Kevin Towers called with 
the news that he had been drafted at 2:30 p.m. The movie was "Major League." 
And, no, he said, he didn't necessarily identify with Wild Thing, the goofy 
relief pitcher played by Charlie Sheen, despite his inconsistent control. 
</P>
<P>
Quite simply, his arm is what has the Padres excited. And it didn't matter that 
he was in high school instead of college. 
</P>
<P>
"College, high school . . . we wanted the best available athlete to us," said 
Randy Smith, Padre director of scouting. 
</P>
<P>
Beckett is the first high school player selected by the Padres in the first 
round since pitcher Jimmy Jones in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
Towers, also a first-round Padre selection in the 1982 June draft, is the Padre 
scout responsible for the Austin, Tex. area and first saw Beckett last fall. 
</P>
<P>
"I said he was Steve Carlton the first time I saw him," Towers said. "He has an 
above-average fastball and a slider in the 80-82 m.p.h. range. In competition, 
he showed fairly good poise for a high school kid, and I liked the way he went 
after hitters." 
</P>
<P>
Beckett, who won't turn 18 until July, thought he might go in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
"I was hoping and praying and dreaming I would," he said. "I was looking at the 
first three rounds. When it happened, it knocked my socks off." 
</P>
<P>
Now, the Padres have to sign him before whisking him off to one of their minor 
league teams this summer. Beckett said he doesn't have an agent, and wouldn't 
comment on what it will take for the Padres to sign him. 
</P>
<P>
He did say, though, that he has enrolled at McLennan Community College in Waco, 
Tex. in case things don't work out with the Padres. If he plays at a community 
college, he would be eligible for next year's major league draft. If he would 
play at a four-year school, rules stipulate that he would have to wait three 
years before being eligible for the draft again. 
</P>
<P>
"My parents want me to do whatever makes me happy," Beckett said. "They're 
behind me, whatever decision I make." 
</P>
<P>
Beckett said he first realized he may have the tools to play professional 
baseball last summer, when his fastball first reached the 90 m.p.h. range. He 
said it happened in a summer league game, coincidentally, against fellow Texan 
Todd Van Poppel's team. Van Poppel was the most highly publicized high school 
player in this year's draft, but wasn't chosen until 14th overall -- by Oakland 
-- because he made it clear that he will attend the University of Texas. 
</P>
<P>
"In the south part of the state -- my region -- (Beckett's) name was the big 
name," Towers said. "He was the guy going into the season that everybody wanted 
to see." 
</P>
<P>
Beckett throws hard, mostly fastballs and sliders. He said he has been working 
on his curve, and needs to work on a change-up. 
</P>
<P>
"The only thing I've needed to do against competition so far is throw a 
fastball, slider and occasional curve," he said. 
</P>
<P>
One other thing. Beckett says he is 6-5, but he said doctors say he's 6-6. 
</P>
<P>
Why? 
</P>
<P>
"Six-six seems kind of Amazonish," he said. "I should be playing basketball if 
I'm 6-6." 
</P>
<P>
Oh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
